In article <Bx1o2L.AMz@access.digex.com> jthomas@access.digex.com (Joe Thomas) writes:
>   In all the posts I've read about PKP's patent claims over RSA public
>key encryption, I have never seen anyone mention when the patent is due 
>to expire.  I was under the impression that U.S. patent protection is only
>good for 17 years (I believe that's true for drugs, anyway).  RSA papers
>go back to the mid 70s.  Is RSA going to be in the public domain soon?
>   I've seen posts to this group quoting from PKP's patent.  How about if

The RSA patent, #4,405,829, was awarded on 9/20/83.  It expires on 9/20/00.
Diffie-Hellman, patent #4,200,770 was awarded on 3/29/80.
Merkle-Hellman knapsacks, patent #4,218,582, was awarded on 8/19/80.
Finally, Pohig-Hellman, parent #4,424,414, was awarded on 3/3/84.

Bruce

